<br>
I'm not arguing that there aren't many characters with moves that are Ryu clones, but the characters themselves are original.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I assume the one you are referring to is KOF 99-there are 3 versions of kyo, which coincidently is part of the story. I wouldn't say it was any different from evil ryu or shin gouki (akuma).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Actually it is, considering you only have to pick Ryu to access any of his other forms. But my point wasn't that Capcom was any better than SNK, just that they BOTH do it.<br>
<br>
And about SFEX, I've never played it. But I know Rival Schools did the same thing. Nearly every single person on that game was a Ryu clone. Then there's something like Marvel v Capcom 2. Sure, there are a lot of people with similar moves, but considering there's over 50 characters, there's still plenty of variety and originality. Even characters that have similar move sets (uppercut, projectile, kick move) aren't always straight clones. Take Cable for example, he has that standard set, but they changed them significantly enough so that you have to use a different strategy using him and playing against him, as well as giving him 2 or 3 unique moves. Obviously, they don't do that with all the characters... but I don't think it's from a lack of originality, just that there's only so many moves to be given out to 50+ characters. Though in a game with few characters, it isn't much of an excuse. <p><html>
